---
const title = "Introduction to HTML";
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro:components";
---

<Layout title={title}>
  <p>
    Here's a diagram illustrating the different structural elements of a basic
    HTML tag:
  </p>
  <img
    src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}images/tag-structure.png`}
    alt="sample sitemap"
  />

  <hr />

  <h2>HTML Page</h2>
  <p>
    The basic boilerplate of an HTML page is below. To generate a new HTML page
    you can use the
    <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3QEU9bphWE0"
      >shortcut to create HTML page</a
    >
    in VS Code (via the <a href="https://emmet.io/">Emmet</a> plugin).
  </p>
  <p>
    Another option is to download
    <a href="https://html5boilerplate.com/">HTML5 Boilerplate</a>, an
    opinionated starter kit with some good conventions.
  </p>
  <Code
    code={`<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Document</title>
  </head>
  <body></body>
</html>`}
    lang="html"
  />

  <hr />

  <h2>Comments:</h2>
  <p>
    Below is an example of a comment in HTML, which can be used to leave notes
    for the developer. While this won't render in the browser, it's still
    displayed when viewing source code.
  </p>

  <Code
    code={`<!-- This is an example of a comment. Comments don't render in the browser -->`}
    lang="html"
  />

  <hr />
  <h2>Headings</h2>
  <p>
    HTML has six headings. Typically, you would only have one &lt;h1&gt; per
    page. Subsequent headlines should follow the respective hierarchy. Bear in
    mind search engines weigh the value of these headings.
  </p>
